Higher levels of sectoral contestation measured as a dissonance between leading national and subnational economic sectors, had a positive effect on state-building. The capacity the state has of enforcing and monitoring building codes throughout the territory rises conditional on higher levels of subnational sectoral contestation. As the historical evidence suggests, lower levels of sectoral inequality marked by the secular emergence of the industrial sector posed credible threats to the landowning elites. Since industrial production required a denser public infrastructure, industrialists were willing to cooperate with the central level and shoulder a national income tax in exchange of public goods. For instance, Chilean industrial elites made a series of political compromises with agricultural incumbents in exchange of having more state services delivered at the local level. In turn, state-led ``meddling'' in individual affairs (such as in private incomes) rose levels of state capacities. In this section I find that the Chilean state was better able to implement at the subnational level nationally designed institutions, particularly building codes, when the main national economic sector did not rule the average subnational locality. I attribute these increments in subnational state-capacities to the incorporation of both elites into the same national project. Being the income tax law (a state-\emph{making} institution) representative of both industrial and agricultural interests, the law achieved quasi-voluntary compliance,\footnote{\citet{Levi:1989lq}.} as taxation was in the interest of both elites. Taxing incomes required the implementation of stronger local bureaucracies and better monitoring technologies. In time, these assets were transfered via spillovers to other state activities, such as justice provision, schooling programs, and others. In other words, there are structural complementarities between taxation and state capacities. As there were asset complementarities between knowing how to tax incomes and expanding the rest of the state, the capabilities of the Chilean state grew endogenously. These results find empirical support for the positive relationship between the emergence of local industrial clusters and higher levels of state-capacities. However, they do not tell us how these sectoral dynamics impacted state-capacities \emph{overtime}, which is what I do next.




